  "answer": "In the Urdu poetic register, as exemplified in Allama Iqbal's *Bang-e-Dara*, **'bulbul'** consistently refers to the nightingale—a conventional symbol of the passionate lover, poet, or restless soul. It is frequently depicted lamenting (*naala-e-bulbul*) or singing (*naghma* or *tarannum*) in the garden (*chaman*) for its beloved, the rose (*gul*), embodying unrequited longing, melancholy, and artistic fervor.[^1][^2][^3][^4]\n\nThis imagery draws from the broader Perso-Urdu ghazal tradition (also present in works by Mirza Ghalib and Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq in the corpus), where the bulbul's song amid beauty and separation mirrors the human condition.[^5]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, \"Rukhsat Ae Bazm-e-Jahan\" (transliteration): \"Hai chaman mera watan, hamsaaya-e-bulbul hoon main\" ([paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/35-rukhsat-ae-bazm-e-jahan/transliteration/#p-2d8d58)).\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, \"Rukhsat Ae Bazm-e-Jahan\" (translation): \"This garden is my home, where songs of Bulbul never end.\" ([paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/35-rukhsat-ae-bazm-e-jahan/translation/#p-2e0f9d)).\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, \"Dard-e-Ishq\" (transliteration): \"Minnat pazeer-e-naala-e-bulbul ka tu na ho\" ([paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/17-dard-e-ishq/transliteration/#p-787d3f)).\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, \"Mehr-e-roshan\" (transliteration): \"Waan bhi kya faryaad-e-bulbul par chaman rota nahin?\" ([paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/32-mehr-e-roshan/transliteration/#p-6d3166)).\n[^5]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-e-Dara Part 3*, \"Falsafa-e-Gham\" (transliteration): \"Jo khizaan na-deeda ho bulbul, woh bulbul hi nahin.\" ([paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/07-falsafa-e-gham/transliteration/#p-c49e89)).",
